AFTER TOUCHDOWN ON THE RUNWAY, THE PILOT HELD THE NOSE WHEEL OFF FOR 
ABOUT 200 FEET OF TRAVEL BY HOLDING THE CONTROL WHEEL BACK. ACCORDING 
TO HIM, THE AIRCRAFT THEN VEERED TO THE LEFT AND HE WAS UNABLE TO STEER IT 
WITH THE RUDDER PEDALS. THE AIRCRAFT WENT OFF THE SIDE OF THE RUNWAY AND 
NOSED OVER ON AN ADJACENT GRASS AREA. AN EXAM OF THE AIRCRAFT REVEALED 
THAT THE NOSE GEAR WAS BENT ABOUT 30 DEGREES TO THE LEFT. THE BRAKES 
TESTED SATISFACTORY AND THE WHEELS ROTATED FREELY. 
